{:itonami.blueprint/id "cloud-itonami-isic-3314"
 :itonami.blueprint/name "Repair of Electrical Equipment"
 :itonami.blueprint/isic-rev5 "3314"
 :itonami.blueprint/domain :manufacturing/electrical-equipment-repair
 :itonami.blueprint/license "AGPL-3.0-or-later"
 :itonami.blueprint/social-impact [:worker-safety :repair-access :circular-economy-repair-over-replace]
 :itonami.blueprint/governor :electrical-equipment-repair-governor
 :itonami.blueprint/robotics false
 :itonami.blueprint/required-technologies [:identity :forms :audit-ledger]
 :itonami.blueprint/optional-technologies []
 :itonami.blueprint/status :public-oss
 :itonami.blueprint/maturity :implemented
 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "`:electrical-equipment-repair-governor` is implemented end-to-end in
 `src/electrical_equipment_repair` as a REPAIR-SHOP OPERATIONS
 COORDINATION actor -- Repair Advisor (LLM proposal-only) ⊣ Repair
 Governor (closed-op-allowlist / equipment-verification / legal-basis /
 unresolved-concern hard-gates). ISIC 3314 covers repair of electrical
 equipment specifically -- motors, generators, transformers and
 switchgear -- distinct from the more specific/other repair classes 3311
 (fabricated metal products), 3312 (machinery and equipment), 3313
 (electronic and optical equipment), 3315 (transport equipment) and the
 residual class 3319 (other equipment). This actor deliberately holds NO
 repair-equipment/diagnostic-tool control authority and NO
 return-to-service/re-energization sign-off authority (both are HARD,
 permanent governor blocks, never overridable by human approval -- see
 `electrical-equipment-repair.governor` ns docstring), the SAME
 coordination-only, narrower-than-4211 shape `cloud-itonami-isic-3320`
 (Installation of Industrial Machinery and Equipment) and
 `cloud-itonami-isic-3319` (Repair of Other Equipment) already established
 in this fleet. Every one of its four proposal ops (`:log-repair-record` /
 `:schedule-repair-operation` / `:flag-safety-concern` / `:order-
 supplies`) carries `:effect :propose` ONLY -- the governor HARD-holds any
 proposal that doesn't (`effect-not-propose-violations`), a structural
 invariant distinguishing this actor from siblings that DO commit
 real-world actuation effects.

 UNLIKE `cloud-itonami-isic-3320` (whose `:schedule-installation-
 operation` ALWAYS escalates to a human, at every phase, because it
 coordinates potential heavy-lift/rigging-equipment dispatch), THIS
 actor's `:schedule-repair-operation` MAY auto-commit at phase 3 when the
 governor is completely clean -- equipment/work-order independently
 verified, a per-jurisdiction de-energization-before-repair legal basis on
 file, and no unresolved safety concern on record. This is the SAME
 escalation shape `cloud-itonami-isic-3319` uses, deliberately extended to
 this class even though electrical equipment (motors, generators,
 transformers, switchgear) carries a genuinely higher intrinsic electrical
 hazard (arc-flash, stored/residual voltage in capacitors, insulation
 breakdown) than 3319's furniture/sporting-goods/musical-instrument
 residual scope: the schedule op itself is still only ever a proposed
 diagnostic/repair/testing WINDOW, never a live-work authorization, a
 repair-equipment/diagnostic-tool control command, or a return-to-service/
 re-energization sign-off -- and this actor's own HARD checks (equipment-
 verification, legal-basis-on-file citing the jurisdiction's own
 de-energization-before-repair duty, no-unresolved-safety-concern) plus
 its forbidden-action-class block on any `:re-energization-sign-off?`
 marker already gate the actual electrical-hazard surface independently
 of phase. `:flag-safety-concern` is the ONLY permanent, unconditional
 `high-stakes` member in `electrical-equipment-repair.governor` -- see
 that ns docstring 'Actuation' section for the full rationale.

 Per-jurisdiction (JPN/USA/DEU) pre-repair de-energization/re-energization
 legal-basis catalog (`electrical-equipment-repair.facts`) with real
 official sources -- all THREE seeded jurisdictions are honestly
 `:qualitative` here (a procedural de-energize-before-work / verify-
 de-energized / qualified-personnel duty, plus (JPN, DEU) an explicit
 pre-re-energization or pre-return-to-service check duty, not a fixed
 numeric notice-lead-time), the same honest-coverage convention
 `installation.facts`/`demolition.facts`/`construction.facts`/`other-
 equipment-repair.facts` establish. This actor does not invent a
 numeric lead-time count where none of its three researched
 jurisdictions' electrical safety law gives one for repair work itself.
 This build ships NO JVM-only interop anywhere in `src/` (no real
 Resend/Twilio transports -- `electrical-equipment-repair.notify` ships
 only the portable mock notifier + `Notifier` protocol seam) per this
 workspace's cljs-first `.cljc` runtime-priority rule. `:flag-safety-
 concern` ALWAYS escalates to a human, at every phase, unconditionally.
 See `docs/` -- README `Actuation` section -- for the full governor-check
 enumeration and the rationale for each hard/soft rule."}
